[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837781927048&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837781927048&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

Harvard offers to be a primary or secondary nameserver for bitnet MX
records if the bitnet "powers" and the NIC ok it.

Note that MX records are the only sure way to get this to work
since some bitnet sites are now using a domain style return address
that refers to a host that has no current record. Also note that
only the bitnet nodes that are not part of a currently legit domain
need to be added, assuming that the operators of the other domains have
( as we at harvard have ) added their bitnet hosts to their namederver
databases even if they do not have a local path to that node. If they have
not, it might get a bit strange.

The ideal setup would have the MX record point to the gateway that is the
fewest bitnet hops away from the requested node.

scott bradner
sob@harvard.*

